Goal: Save your sanity and time by avoiding common MD pitfalls. This guide is designed for beginners and experienced researchers alike.

1). Pre-MD Checklist: Sanity Steps
System Preparation
Clean protein: fix missing residues, add hydrogens.
Validate ligand: charges, bonds, torsions.
Rename ligand residue from PubChem ID to LIG before topology generation.
Remove unwanted molecules (crystallographic waters, extra ions).

Box & Solvation
Use ≥1 nm buffer from protein-ligand complex to box edges.
Solvate carefully; check overlapping waters.
Neutralize system and add physiological ions (~0.15 M NaCl).

Energy Minimization (EM)
Steepest Descent EM first; disable constraints if EM fails.
Check max force < 1000 kJ/mol/nm.
Visual check: no overlapping atoms or stretched bonds.

Equilibration
| Step    | Target | Duration   | Restraints                  | Notes                                              |
| ------- | ------ | ---------- | --------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| **NVT** | 300 K  | 100–500 ps | Protein & ligand restrained | Check RMSD & temperature ±2–5 K                    |
| **NPT** | 1 bar  | 100–500 ps | Same restraints             | Density stabilizes (~1000 kg/m³); pressure ±10 bar |

Production MD
Time step: 2 fs (with hydrogen constraints).
Check temperature, pressure, and forces.
Save checkpoints frequently.

2). Topology Practices
Do NOT edit topol.top manually after EM/equilibration.
Changing atom counts, molecule definitions, or charges manually → MD crashes.
Regenerate topology only when adding/removing molecules (ligands, ions).
Rename ligand residues before topology generation so force field recognizes them.

3). Do’s & Don’ts Cheat Sheet
 DOs
Clean structures and validate ligands.
Rename ligands from PubChem IDs → LIG before generating topologies.
Keep ≥1 nm box buffer, neutralize, and add ions.
EM first (max force <1000 kJ/mol/nm).
NVT/NPT equilibration before production; monitor RMSD, T, P, density.
Use GROMACS + CHARMM36-JUL2022.
Save checkpoints and logs; visualize frequently.

 DON’Ts
Don’t skip EM, NVT, or NPT.
Don’t leave overlapping atoms or distorted structures.
Don’t manually edit topol.top after equilibration.
Don’t run MD with extreme forces or LINCS failures unresolved.
Don’t use ligand PubChem IDs without renaming.

4). Common Error Texts to Watch For

During EM, NVT, NPT, or production MD, these errors indicate potential system problems:

| Error                                          | What It Means                | How to Fix                                                     |
| ---------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `LINCS WARNING: relative constraint deviation` | Bonds stretched beyond 30°   | Check topology, constraints, EM convergence                    |
| `Maximum force > 1e+18 kJ/mol/nm`              | System exploded              | Inspect ligand/protein clashes, solvation overlaps, restraints |
| `Potential energy = huge number`               | EM failed                    | Check box size, topology, or ligand parametrization            |
| `Failed to read topology`                      | `topol.top` altered manually | Restore original topol.top; regenerate if ligand added         |
| `Atom not recognized`                          | Ligand residue name invalid  | Rename ligand (LIG) before topology generation                 |


Tip: Always inspect PDB snapshots after EM/NVT/NPT to catch distorted bonds or steric clashes.

5). Quick Sanity Tips

Small EM time steps: 1–2 fs.
Visualize system often (PyMOL or VMD).
Backup original structures and .mdp files.
Document all parameters for reproducibility.
If EM/NVT/NPT repeatedly fails → check ligand topology, restraints, and box size first.



